At the top is one of these ESP32 modules with a fisheye lens camera and an infrared LED that I scavenged from a Raspberry Pi device.
If this plastic box has an unusual shape, it's because of the pivoting side panel of the nesting box. I bought it that way and couldn't modify it, so I had to design my installation around it.
Since there is no electricity in the garden, the entire system is powered by a solar panel and a 18650 cell with a capacity of 2600 mAh.
I did not photograph the cell or the charger, but here is a photo of the panel.
The gray box suspended on the side of the nesting box houses the battery.
At full charge, it gives me about 4 hours of energy.
I would call this a feature. This way, birds can also have a bit of privacy.
